Introduction ¶

Anomalous sounds can indicate a fault in a piece of machinery, and early detection of them would prevent the propagation of damage. Because of that, the scientific machine learning community is putting a lot of attention on anomalous sound detection (ASD).

ASD is the task of identifying whether the sound emitted from an object is normal or anomalous.

Anomaly detection techniques can be categorized as:.

  • Supervised anomaly detection requires the entire dataset to be labeled "normal" or "anomaly". This technique is a binary classification task.
  • Semi-supervised anomaly detection requires only data considered "normal" to be labeled. In this technique, the model will learn what "normal" data are like.
  • Unsupervised anomaly detection involves unlabeled data. In this technique, the model will learn which data is "normal" and "anomaly".

State of the art ¶

The paper Anomalous Sound Detection with Machine Learning: A Systematic Review shows that the ToyADMOS, MIMII, and Mivia datasets, the Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients (MFCC) method for extracting features, the Autoencoder (AE) and Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) models of ML, the AUC and F1-score evaluation methods were most cited.

The three most cited datasets were: ToyADMOS, MIMII, and Mivia.

  • The ToyADMOS dataset is a machine operating sound dataset that has approximately 540 hours of normal sound and approximately 12,000 hours of anomalous sound. ToyADMOS was designed to detect audio anomalies in research involving machine operation.
  • The MIMII dataset is a data set for investigation and inspection of defective industrial machines. It contains the sounds generated from four types of industrial machines (valves, pumps, fans and slide rails).
  • The Mivia dataset is an audio dataset composed of 6,000 events considered to be vigilance (glass break, shots and screams).

The most used metrics were:

  • AUC-ROC is a performance evaluation that involves classification problems with thresholds. AUC represents a degree of separability and ROC is a probability curve. The higher the AUC, the better the model for predicting a particular class.
  • F1-score measures the accuracy of an ML model. It is widely used in classification.

Project ¶

This project is my attempt to solve the task Unsupervised Detection of Anomalous Sounds for Machine Condition Monitoring from the 2020 DCASE Challenge for pumps.

It consists of two steps:

  1. develop machine learning algorithms to distinguish anomalous sound from normal sounds in Jupyter notebooks using Tensorflow
  2. put in production the best model in a Streamlit web app with Tensorflow serving

My goals for this projects are:

  1. Experiment with different audio features (spectrogram, mel-spectrogram, log mel-spectrogram...)
  2. Replicate the MIMMI paper model and 2020 DCASE challenge baseline model
  3. Find a model that improves the metrics of those models.
  4. Experiment with MLOps best practices

Dataset ¶

The dataset of this project is the development dataset of pumps from the second task of the 2020 DCASE Challenge, a simplified version of the MIMII dataset (audio files have only one channel instead of eight channels).

The dataset contains 3349 audio files for training and 856 audio files for testing. Each recording is a single-channel 10-sec length audio that includes both a target machine's operating sound and environmental noise.

To speed up the training and manipulation of the audio samples, I have transformed the development dataset of pumps from the second task of the 2020 DCASE Challenge into a Tensorflow dataset. The original dataset of pumps has two folders (train and test) and filenames explain whether the audio sample is normal or anomaly and which machine it belongs to.

My Tensorflow dataset has the following information:

  • audio holds the values of the audio file. Audios last 10 seconds and were recorded at 16kHz with a resolution of 16 bits
  • audio/id is the id number of the audio
  • audio/machine is the number of the pump (00, 02, 04, 06)
  • audio/split shows the folders where the file comes from (train or test)
  • label shows whether the sound is normal or anomaly
FeaturesDict({
    'audio': Audio(shape=(160000,), dtype=tf.int64),
    'audio/id': Text(shape=(), dtype=tf.string),
    'audio/machine': Text(shape=(), dtype=tf.string),
    'audio/split': ClassLabel(shape=(), dtype=tf.int64, num_classes=2),
    'label': ClassLabel(shape=(), dtype=tf.int64, num_classes=2),
})

Methodology ¶

I have created the following anomaly detectors:

  • Supervised anomaly detectors
    1. Spectrogram supervised anomaly detector
    2. Mel-spectrogram supervised anomaly detector
  • Semi-supervised anomaly detectors
    1. Spectral centroid semi-supervised anomaly detector
    2. Log-mel spectrogram supervised anomaly detector (Challenge baseline model)
    3. Log-mel spectrogram supervised anomaly detector (MIMMI paper model)

Supervised anomaly detector ¶

For the supervised anomaly detectors, I use the convolutional neural network (CNN) architecture.

Instead of extracting the audio feature (spectrogram or Mel-spectrogram) to use it as the input for the CNN, I use a custom Keras layer that extracts the audio feature. Using custom Keras layers has two main advantages:

  • the input to the model is the audio itself so the Streamlit web app doesn't need to manipulate it to feed the model
  • the custom layer is compatible with AutoKeras

These two models use the same architecture, the only difference is the custom layer that extracts the audio feature (spectrogram or Mel-spectrogram).

Semi-supervised anomaly detector ¶

For the semi-supervised anomaly detectors, I use the architecture autoencoder (AE), a popular approach for this kind of problems, as the paper Anomalous Sound Detection with Machine Learning: A Systematic Review shows.

The main characteristicts of an autoencoder are:

  • The output layer has the same number of nodes as the input layer.
  • The middle layer has much less nodes than the input.

Source: An Introduction to Neural Networks and Autoencoders

The purpose of an autoencoder is to reconstruct its inputs minimizing the difference between the input and the output, the reconstruction error.

The anomaly detector will learn how normal sounds look like and give smaller reconstruction error for normal sounds than for anomaly sounds.

Source: AWS

The anomaly detector distinguishes anomalous sounds from normal sounds based on a threshold.

$$ f(x) = \begin{cases} 1, \text{ normal if } x \lt threhold \\ 0, \text{ anomaly if } x \geq threshold \end{cases} $$

I set the threshold value to be one standard deviation above the mean of the reconstruction error in the training set.

The differences between the three models are:

  • the audio feature that the model uses as input and output
  • the internal layers of the neural network

Spectral centroid semi-supervised anomaly detector ¶

This model uses the spectral centroid of the audios as the input. It is calculated as the weighted mean of the frequencies present in the signal, determined using a Fourier transform, with their magnitudes as the weights

This audio feature is not very popular as the paper Anomalous Sound Detection with Machine Learning: A Systematic Review shows, but it is one of the few 1D audio features that I can use.

Conclusions ¶

  1. The copycat models perform much worse than the models described in the MIMII paper and the 2020 DCASE Challenge. It seems Tensorflow calculates the STFT different than the librosa does.

  2. Supervised anomaly detectors perform much better than semi-supervised ones and the performance doesn't change significantly when the model uses another audio feature.

  3. Supervised models don't perform homogenously among all machines, so the machine_id could be an important feature to improve the performance of the models. To add the machine_id, I would choose:

    • two-step training: firstly, train a general model with data of the four models, and later get four models through fine-tuning with data of each machine.
    • use the machine_id as input in the neural networks

Lessons learnt ¶

  1. Tensorflow datasets are very convenient to create pipelines and speed up training. However, third-party libraries manipulation and debugging are much harder because Tensorflow datasets use graph execution mode. According to Tensorflow API documentation of map function, "irrespective of the context in which map_func is defined (eager vs. graph), tf.data traces the function and executes it as a graph."

  2. Replicate the 2020 DCASE Challenge baseline model and the MIMII paper model were impossible because Tensorflow functions for signal manipulation are less developed than Pytorch/torchaudio and Librosa. In hindsight, replicate those models would have been easier with Pytorch or Torchlibrosa.

  3. Train a semi-supervised anomaly detector is much more difficult than train a supervised anomaly detector because common guidelines for supervised machine learning don't apply to semi-supervised machine learning.

  4. Docker containers and Docker compose simplify and ensure the replicability of my code.

Appendix ¶

MLOps ¶

Among all the tools to ensure the reproducibility of my code and the track my dataset and models, I have decided to use Docker, Docker compose and Tensorflow Serving. The Tensorflow dataset that I created helps me to do version control of the data.

I have experimented with CML/Github Actions and MLflow, but. I have decided not to use because:

  • CML or Github Actions seems to be more suitable for smaller datasets and training times
  • it is easier to serve a Tensorflow model with Tensorflow Serving that with MLflow.

Docker ¶

To ensure the reproducibility of my code, I use four Docker images:

  • development_tensorboad: the image for Tensorboard. The Dockrefile installs Tensorboard package in a 3.8 Python Docker image.
  • development_notebook: the image for the Jupyter notebooks. The Dockerfile installs the required packages in a 3.7 Python Docker image.
  • production_frontend: the image for the Streamlit app. The Dockerfile installs Streamlit package in a 3.8 Python Docker image.
  • tensorflow/serving: a Tensorflow serving Docker image from Docker hub.

The Docker image for the Jupyter notebooks is different from the Docker image for Tensorboard and Streamlit because the wordcloud package wheel is not available for Python 3.8.

Docker compose ¶

I use Docker compose to run the required containers for production and development environment:

  • Development Docker compose file runs the Docker container for the Jupyter notebooks and Tensorboard server and mounts several volumes for the notebooks.

  • Production Docker compose file runs the Docker image for the Streamlit web app and Tensorflow serving, creates a network to connect them and mounts several volumes for the source code of the app and the Tensorflow models for the Tensorflow serving.

Tensorflow Serving ¶

Tensorflow Serving as a backend for the Streamlit helps me:

  • to reduce the size of the Streamlit image because it doesn't need Tensorflow to make predictions
  • to track the models in production because Tensorflow Serving uses the model that has the higher version

Tensorflow Serving knows the name and the files of the models from the models.config file. To add a new model, I need to declare it in the models.config file and mount a new volume in the Docker compose file.

Streamlit ¶

I have designed the Streamlit web app as a four-step game. So, users can test themselves and compare their guesses against my trained models' predictions.

In the first step, the user can choose a trained model. Between the five models that I have trained, the user can only choose the supervised anomaly detectors because any of the three semi-supervised anomaly detectors work very poor.

In the second step, the user can select an audio file to guess whether its sound is normal or anomalous. To make it easier, the user can train themselves with normal audios from the same machine. The user can listen to the audio and inspect its wave plot, spectrogram and Mel-spectrogram.

In the third step, the user can pick whether the sound is normal or anomalous.

In the last step, the user can check the true label of the audio label and compare his guess against the chosen model's predictions. The user can also check how sure the model is with its prediction.

The web app has two big limitations:

  • it chooses audio files in a determinist way because Streamlit always refresh the web app after any user interaction. So, every time the user chooses another audio to train himself, the web app refreshes and shows different audios, even from a different machine.
  • the wave plot, spectrogram and Mel-spectrogram are precomputed to speed up the interaction between the web and the user.
